"Abstract It has become a cliche to refer to every recently adopted piece of European Union legislation as “long-awaited.” However, this designation is certainly true for the Telecommunications Data Protection Directive.1 As the requirements of the EU Data Protection Directive are now being finally implemented, it has become increasingly important to fill in the gaps in that directive regarding telecoms personal data. Furthermore, the growth in telecoms competition and number of telecoms providers raises the importance of dealing with privacy issues in a coherent way. This rationale applies equally to the importance of secure and reliable telecommunications services to industry and individuals. Mark Naftel analyses the EU Telecoms Data Protection Directive."
